[In the past 24 hours, according to the report at the source URL, the tally of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in South Korea has increased by 45 cases with 0 new deaths, compared with 26 cases and 1 new death in the previous day (19 Jul 2020). The daily newly confirmed case count has been at or below 100 for 97 consecutive days. There were 20 locally transmitted cases: Seoul (18), Gyeonggi (1), and Jeju (1); and 25 imported cases: airport quarantine (18), Seoul (3), Daegu (2), Gyeonggi (1), Gyeongbuk (1). 12 provinces reported no newly confirmed cases (compared with 7 provinces yesterday, 19 Jul 2020). Information on the cases in Seoul is not available at the time of preparation of this update.

The overall impression hasn't changed. Lifting of measures was accompanied by increases in locally acquired infections through increasing clusters related to gatherings of people at employment (bringing it outside employment to contacts) and in houses of worship, and bars and clubs. Contact tracing and isolation seem to have had an impact. Now importations are playing a major role in the country as well. Looking at both China and South Korea, I suspect that importations may result in the occasional silent spread from asymptomatic infections which may be missed through the testing (false negatives). A superspreading event may result, leading to a recognized cluster, which can ultimately be interrupted until the next cycle occurs. The increase in cases in the past few days has been paralleled by increases in reported deaths.

A map of South Korea showing provinces can be seen at https://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/korea-south-administrative-map.htm and a HealthMap/ProMED map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=7595820,195. - Mod.MPP]

