Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed cases of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215.

In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:

- The Americas region reported 58.1% of the global newly reported cases and 60.8% of newly reported deaths for this 24-hour period, maintaining its dominance as the most severely affected region, having reported more than 7.5 million cases. The USA reported 50.1% (66 963) cases, Brazil 21.4% (28 532), Colombia 6.4% (8560), Mexico 5.7% (7615), Guatemala 3.2% (4233), Peru 3.0% (3963), Argentina 2.4% (3223), and Chile 1.6% (2084).

- The European region reported 7.5% of the global newly reported cases and 9.6% of the newly confirmed deaths globally. Russia reported 34.6% (5940) of the regional newly confirmed cases, followed by Kazakhstan reporting 8.7% (1499), Israel 8.4% (1440), Turkey 5.4% (924), Romania 4.5% (767), the UK 4.2% (726), Ukraine 3.8% (651), Kyrgyzstan 3.6% (611), Uzbekistan 3.1% (537), Serbia 2.3% (396), Azerbaijan 2.3% (388), and Poland 2.1% (358).

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 5.6% of the global newly reported cases and 9.0% of global newly reported fatalities. Saudi Arabia reported 19.6% (2504) of the regional newly reported cases, followed by Iraq 18.1% (2310), Iran 17.1% (2182), Pakistan 12.4% (1587), Oman 9.0% (1157), Egypt 4.7% (603), Palestinian Authority 3.6% (465), Bahrain 3.3% (418), Qatar 2.7% (340), and Kuwait 2.3% (300).

- The African region reported 7.9% of the global newly reported cases and 2.8% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 74.2% (13 449) of the newly reported cases in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Ethiopia 3.9% (704), Ghana 3.3% (607), Kenya 3.3% (603), Nigeria 3.1% (556), Algeria 3.0% (535), and Cote d'Ivoire 2.3% (423).

- The Western Pacific region reported 1.5% of the global newly reported cases and 1.3% of global deaths. The Philippines reported 63.2% (2152) of the newly reported cases in the region, followed by Japan 13.3% (454), Australia 10.6% (361), Singapore 7.5% (257), China 3.8% (131), and South Korea 0.76% (26).

- The South East Asia region reported 19.5% of the global newly reported cases and 16.53% of global deaths. India reported 90.4% (40 425) of newly reported cases in the region, followed by Bangladesh 5.5% (2459) and Indonesia 3.7% (1639).

Impression: The overall picture is basically the same. The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed cases on a daily basis followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe followed by the Eastern Mediterranean, followed by the Africa region and the Western Pacific representing the lowest daily caseload of all the regions. The progression has been the initial "surge" in the Western Pacific region, followed by the surge in the European region and its decline; the entry and surging of the Americas region without any decrease, and the gradual and persistent increase in the South East Asia region; the increase then plateauing of the Eastern Mediterranean region, the slow but steady increase in the Africa region, and a slight increase in the Western Pacific region. Countries that are showing increased activity include Iraq, Guatemala. It appears as though Russia has peaked and is now declining.

Figure 2. The epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 20 Jul 2020, at the source URL above is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the above text. - Mod.MPP]

