Total number of reported deaths: 613 213
Total number of worldwide cases: 14 852 700
Number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours: 212 325

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to the data on the Worldometer website, the total number of reported cases of COVID-19 worldwide is now 14 852 700, with reports of cases by 217 countries and territories worldwide. The global case count rose by 1.5% in the past 24 hours. The USA and Brazil are still the most severely affected countries in terms of cumulative case counts, although India has been rapidly increasing, with daily case counts around 40 000.

In the past 24 hours, the USA reported the most newly confirmed cases (62 879) followed by India (36 810), and Brazil (21 749). The total cumulative case counts for the top 5 countries (USA, Brazil, India, Russia, South Africa) represent over half of the total cases reported globally (56.5%). A global total of 613 213 deaths have been reported, an increase of 4356 deaths in the past 24 hours.

In descending rank order, the USA is number one for the number of newly confirmed cases in the past 24 hours, followed by India, Brazil, South Africa, Colombia, Russia, Mexico, Spain, Peru, and Argentina. Argentina displaced Saudi Arabia on this list. All these countries are currently experiencing major community-based transmission and considered global hot spots. The range in the top 10 daily newly confirmed cases goes from 4019 to 62 879.

Comparing the 7-day averages of daily confirmed cases from the past 7 days and those from 8-14 days ago, there is an increase of 8.0%. I suspect this is watered down by the weekend days when multiple countries do not report cases.

Impression: The SARS-CoV-2 is still actively being transmitted in all regions of the world, and many countries are showing increases in their daily newly confirmed case counts. That being said, the most severely affected region is the Americas, with cases increasing on a daily basis even though the comparative 7-day average suggests things may be slowing down (or reporting is slowing down). - Mod.MPP]
